{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f02ce38-146c-465b-8b6a-14311a5cd3dd","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None | `--auth None` (default) |\n| Individual Accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Work/School (Azure AD) | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Multi-org Azure AD | `--auth MultiOrg` |\n| Windows Auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Example:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth Individual\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need custom token validation. Would you like help scaffolding a specific setup?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ddc84244-1dd9-4b00-acb9-687643a903d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":252,"requestId":"C801:3F1DAE:6D3039C:757599E:6A03CC08"},"id":"6a977b05-3cea-418d-84bb-dfc3c3219b96","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:55:43.739Z","parentId":"ffd20a35-7629-4785-830e-727f81d833ad"}
